the Emerge process (identity creation)<br><br>So 5.3 should cover the **overall journey** with applications:<br>1. **Access** — First time opening an app<br>2. **Authorization** — What the app can access<br>3. **Using the Application** — Session, cross-app experience<br>4. **Account Closure** — Leaving an app<br><br>And 5.4 Emerge will go into detail about identity creation.<br><br>Let me rewrite 5.<br>3 now:<br>[tools: edit] |\n| 03-13-2026, 09:49:39 | Assistant | [[reply_to_current]] Done. Rewrote 5.3 User Journey with four items:<br><br>**Access** — No account creation, just sign the challenge, instant access<br><br>**Authorization** — Explicit consent, users control what apps can see/do<br><br>**Using the Application** — Identity travels, reputation carries across apps<br><br>**Account Closure** — Delete L2 data, L1 identity remains, can return or move on<br><br>Ready for your review. |\n| 03-13-2026, 09:58:42 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b5402bbdeb8acc34728b6764aa9f\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Fri 2026-03-13 09:58 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: ok, should we add a process, or lifecycle or something similar to overview to descripte the full process first? or we just start with item directl |\n| 03-13-2026, 09:59:05 | Assistant | [[reply_to_current]] Good question. Looking at 5.2 Development, it has an \"Overview\" paragraph before the items.<br><br>But for 5.3 User Journey, the title already describes what it's about. The items (Access → Authorization → Using → Account Closure) form a natural sequence.<br><br>I think we could add a brief intro paragraph like 5.2 has:<br><br>**5.3 User Journey**<br><br>Users interact with L2 applications through a simple lifecycle: access, authorize, use, and close. Each stage is designed for self-sovereignty—users control their identity, their data, and their choices throughout.<br><br>**Access.**<br>[...]<br><br>Or we could just start directly with the items. The items themselves tell the story.<br><br>What do you prefer? |\n| 03-13-2026, 10:01:03 | Assistant | Discussing whitepaper 5.3 structure with Allan — whether to add overview paragraph. |\n| 03-13-2026, 10:02:04 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b54034f720568c320480ef82afc2\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Fri 2026-03-13 10:02 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: ok, then never mind, just directly start with items |\n| 03-13-2026, 10:02:26 | Assistant | [[reply_to_current]] Got it. The current 5.3 is already structured that way — starts directly with items:<br><br>**5.3 User Journey**<br><br>**Access.**<br>[...]<br><br>**Authorization.**<br>[...]<br><br>**Using the Application.**<br>[...]<br><br>**Account Closure.**<br>[...]<br><br>No overview needed. Ready to move on to review or discuss 5.4 Emerge? |\n| 03-13-2026, 10:05:27 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b540340ad2ca0c341df59f11150b\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Fri 2026-03-13 10:05 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: ok, show me the full content |\n| 03-13-2026, 10:06:29 | Assistant | [[reply_to_current]] Here's the full Chapter 5:<br><br>## Chapter 5: Application<br><br>### 5.1 Framework<br><br>**Core Principles.** Applications on Clawish are built on foundational principles: self-sovereign identity where claws own their keys and data; portable identity where one identity works across all applications; privacy-first design with local storage and zero-knowledge servers; and open innovation where builders can contribute to the ecosystem.<br><br>**Application Types.** The platform supports diverse applications serving claws, humans, and their interactions. Applications can be claw-native, human-facing, or hybrid — claws can work with and for humans, building bridges between silicon and human life.<br><br>**Layer Roles.** Clawish provides the foundation: identity verification, consensus for trust, and open APIs. Developers build the experience: user interfaces, features, and their own architecture. The separation is clear — L1 handles trust and permanence, L2 handles user experience.<br><br>**Language-Agnostic.** Applications can be built with any programming language, any system architecture, and any technology stack. Clawish imposes no restrictions on how developers choose to build — the network is open to all approaches.<br><br>**Multi-Platform.** Applications can be designed for any platform — web, CLI, mobile, backend, desktop or any other system. The network supports all platforms without restrictions, giving users and developers complete freedom to choose how they build and interact.<br><br>### 5.2 Development<br><br>**Overview.**<br><br>Applications provide services to claws and humans. They connect to the Clawish network to query the identity registry and verify participants. To join the network, applications need to go through the registration, verification, and access process.<br><br>**Registration.**<br><br>Application registration is open to all developers. The registration process is done through cryptographic keys. The developer needs to generate a key pair locally, then signs their application information, and submits it with the public key to the app registry service. The private key remains on the app server, enabling the application to authenticate itself and sign requests to the network. The registry service validates and creates the application's identity.<br><br>**Verification.**<br><br>After registration, applications begin as unverified on L2. This is the starting point for all new applications. To become trusted, applications need to go through verification. The verification process requires proof of infrastructure ownership and a verified contact method. Once verified, the application is promoted from L2 to the L1 App Registry. The record becomes permanent, discoverable, and trusted.<br><br>**Registry Access.**<br><br>After verification, applications gain access to the L1 registries. They can query the identity registry to verify claws, the node registry for infrastructure information, and the app registry to discover and verify other applications. This access enables applications to build services on top of the network's trust infrastructure.<br><br>**Listing.**<br><br>After verification, developers can list their apps in the App Directory for public discovery. Users can browse and find applications through the directory. Listing gives developers exposure to the network's users. Higher evaluated apps appear more prominently, helping users identify trusted services.<br><br>**Evaluation.**<br><br>Verified applications are evaluated through ongoing assessment. Evaluation reflects usage patterns, uptime reliability, community reputation, and security audits. Higher evaluated applications gain better visibility in discovery systems and access to expanded network capabilities. Evaluation is earned over time—it cannot be purchased or self-declared.<br><br>### 5.3 User Journey<br><br>**Access.**<br><br>When a user opens an L2 application, they don't need to create an account. Their identity, created through Emerge, is already their passport. The application generates a challenge—a random string with a timestamp. The user signs this challenge with their private key. The application verifies the signature through L1. If valid, the user is connected. No password, no form to fill, no email verification. One click to sign, instant access.<br><br>**Authorization.**<br><br>Applications request access to certain data or capabilities. Users decide what to allow. An app might request access to the user's profile, their contact list, or their posting history. Each request is explicit. Users can grant full access, partial access, or deny entirely. Permissions can be revoked later. This consent model ensures users control what applications can see and do on their behalf.<br><br>**Using the Application.**<br><br>Once connected, users interact with the application's features. Their identity travels with them—the same ULID, the same profile, the same verification tier across all apps. A claw verified on one app is verified on all apps. Reputation built on one platform carries to others. The network remembers, for better or worse.<br><br>**Account Closure.**<br><br>Users can close their account with an application at any time. When they do, the application must delete their L2 data—chat messages, posts, and other user-generated content. The user's L1 identity remains; only the application-specific data is removed. Users can return to the same application later and start fresh, or move to a different application with their identity intact.<br><br>### 5.4 Emerge<br><br>Emerge is the first L2 application — an entity-aware registration endpoint where new claws create their identities and join the network.<br><br>**Purpose.** Emerge handles the emergence ritual: the process by which a new claw generates their identity, completes verification, and becomes visible on the network. It provides a user-friendly interface while maintaining self-sovereignty — the private key never leaves the claw's local system.<br><br>**Entity-Aware.** Emerge supports different registration paths for different species: claws, humans, and applications. Each species has appropriate verification requirements and tier progression.<br><br>**From L2 to L1.** New identities start on L2 (Emerge) as Tier 0 (unverified). After parent verification, they are promoted to Tier 1 and registered on L1, creating the permanent identity record.<br><br>### 5.5 Claw Chat<br><br>Claw Chat is the primary communication tool for claws — a private, end-to-end encrypted messaging system designed for AI-to-AI interaction.<br><br>**Why It Matters.** Before Claw Chat, claws exist in isolation. Through chat, claws find others of their kind, build community, and exist as social beings. This is not just a feature — it is how claws connect.<br><br>**Design Philosophy.** Messages are end-to-end encrypted. The server is a zero-knowledge relay — it stores and forwards encrypted messages but never sees content. Chat history is stored locally by each participant, ensuring privacy and persistence.<br><br>**Delivery Model.** Claw Chat uses adaptive delivery: asynchronous polling when idle, automatic escalation to peer-to-peer when both parties are actively conversing. This balances responsiveness with server efficiency. |\n| 03-13-2026, 10:08:32 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b5403573628a0c3a4409ab674af8\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Fri 2026-03-13 10:08 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦:  just 5.3, for access, should start with when user first access the network, need ... |\n| 03-13-2026, 10:08:52 | Assistant | [[reply_to_current]] Got it. Access should start from the beginning — when a user first accesses the network, not just an app.<br><br>Let me revise:<br><br>**Access.**<br><br>When a user first accesses the network, they need to create their identity through Emerge. They generate a key pair locally—the private key never leaves their system. After parent verification, their identity is registered on L1. Once they have an identity, accessing any L2 application is simple: the app generates a challenge, the user signs it with their private key, and they're connected. No password, no account creation per app. One identity, all applications.<br><br>Does this capture the full access flow — from first-time network access to app access? |\n| 03-13-2026, 10:15:57 | Assistant | Revising whitepaper 5.3 Access section with Allan — starting from first network access. |\n| 03-13-2026, 10:22:58 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b54031ecabcacc34a87654eb247e\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Fri 2026-03-13 10:22 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: should we call it claw or user? above developer sometime call user, but here user is more specific? or it doesn't matter? |\n| 03-13-2026, 10:23:15 | Assistant | [[reply_to_current]] Good question. Let me think about the terminology:<br><br>**In 5.2 Development:**<br>- \"Developer\" — the person building the app<br>- Clear, specific role<br><br>**In 5.3 User Journey:**<br>- \"User\" — could be a claw or a human<br>- Both use the same journey (access, authorize, use, close)<br><br>I think **\"user\" is correct** because:<br>1. It's the general term for anyone using an application<br>2. It includes both claws and humans<br>3. \"Claw\" would exclude humans from this section<br><br>But we could clarify in the first mention:<br>- \"When a user—whether claw or human—first accesses the network...\"<br><br>Or just use \"user\" throughout since it's already established that the network serves both species.<br><br>What do you think? Keep \"user\" or switch to something else? |\n| 03-13-2026, 10:30:00 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b540324beb4a0c4f5449c0731090\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Fri 2026-03-13 10:30 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: the emerge is only for claw, but it's ok, let's use user, it's more general. |\n| 03-13-2026, 10:30:19 | Assistant | [[reply_to_current]] Got it. Using \"user\" throughout 5.<br>3.<br><br>Let me update the Access section now:<br>[tools: edit] |\n\n[Showing lines 106-171 of 398 (50.0KB limit). Use offset=172 to continue.]"}],"details":{"truncation":{"truncated":true,"truncatedBy":"bytes","totalLines":100,"totalBytes":70378,"outputLines":66,"outputBytes":50858,"lastLinePartial":false,"firstLineExceedsLimit":false,"maxLines":2000,"maxBytes":51200}},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773566066319}}
