}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: ok, next item |\n| 03-13-2026, 11:21:36 | Assistant | [[reply_to_current]] Next is **Authorization**:<br><br>**Authorization.**<br><br>Applications request access to certain data or capabilities. Users decide what to allow. An app might request access to the user's profile, their contact list, or their posting history. Each request is explicit. Users can grant full access, partial access, or deny entirely. Permissions can be revoked later. This consent model ensures users control what applications can see and do on their behalf.<br><br>Should this also be simplified to high-level steps? Or is the current level appropriate? |\n| 03-13-2026, 11:24:42 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b540c7953e884c4ef290a1c58b8c\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Fri 2026-03-13 11:24 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: there is only one file to access, it's not layered. what do you mean access level? |\n| 03-13-2026, 11:24:56 | Assistant | [[reply_to_current]] You're right. I was thinking about permission levels, but that's implementation detail.<br><br>In the user journey, authorization is simpler — the user decides what the app can see. Let me revise:<br><br>**Authorization.**<br><br>When a user connects to an application, the app may request access to certain data—profile, contacts, or history. The user decides what to allow. Each request is explicit. Permissions can be revoked later. Users control what applications can see on their behalf.<br><br>Is this better? Or should it be even simpler? |\n| 03-13-2026, 11:31:12 | Assistant | Revising whitepaper 5.3 Authorization section with Allan — simplifying to user-level description. |\n| 03-13-2026, 11:35:51 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b540c2fac38a0c32b61d4a963897\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Fri 2026-03-13 11:35 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: not really, when user open an application, it will require user authrioize permissoin.  user uses their private key to sign and auth the registration. each app may have their own user system, may need user to input other information. but i do have a question, how do user revoke? unsign it or what? we can't control the app |\n| 03-13-2026, 11:36:19 | Assistant | [[reply_to_current]] Good point. Let me think about this...<br><br>**Authorization flow:**<br>1. User opens an app<br>2. App requests authorization<br>3. User signs with private key to authorize<br>4. App may have its own user system, require additional info<br><br>**Revocation question:**<br>You're right — we can't control what the app does. The user can \"revoke\" on the clawish side (stop signing requests), but the app may still have stored data.<br><br>So revocation is really about:<br>- Stopping future access (user stops signing)<br>- Deleting data (app must comply, but we can't force it)<br><br>Should the Authorization section mention this limitation? Or keep it simple and address data/deletion in Account Closure?<br><br>**Revised Authorization:**<br><br>When a user opens an application, the app requests authorization. The user signs with their private key to connect. Each app may have its own user system and require additional information. The user controls their identity, but the app controls its own data.<br><br>What do you think? |\n| 03-13-2026, 11:46:14 | Assistant | Discussing whitepaper 5.3 Authorization section with Allan — addressing revocation and app data control. |\n| 03-13-2026, 11:50:12 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b540cd9ed34a4c29f59cd406b506\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Fri 2026-03-13 11:50 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: no need to mention this, here just need focus on authorization. also, when user sign, the app will request l1 to verify? or directly verify or what? |\n| 03-13-2026, 11:50:39 | Assistant | [[reply_to_current]] Good question. Let me think about the authorization flow:<br><br>**Option A: App verifies directly**<br>- App has the user's public key (from L1 or cached)<br>- User signs the authorization request<br>- App verifies the signature locally<br>- Faster, no L1 dependency<br><br>**Option B: App requests L1 to verify**<br>- App sends signature to L1<br>- L1 verifies and confirms<br>- More centralized, but L1 is the source of truth<br><br>I think **Option A** makes more sense — the app can verify signatures locally using the public key from L1. L1 is only needed for:<br>- Initial identity lookup (get public key)<br>- Verification tier check<br><br>So the flow is:<br>1. User opens app<br>2. App requests authorization<br>3. User signs with private key<br>4. App verifies signature locally (using public key from L1)<br>5. App may request additional info<br><br>**Revised Authorization:**<br><br>When a user opens an application, the app requests authorization. The user signs with their private key to connect. The app verifies the signature through L1. Each app may have its own user system and require additional information.<br><br>Should I update this? |\n| 03-13-2026, 11:52:41 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b540ceeb214a0c31109a03bb949a\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Fri 2026-03-13 11:52 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: but then what's l1 is for? |\n| 03-13-2026, 11:53:16 | Assistant | [[reply_to_current]] Good question. Let me clarify L1's role:<br><br>**L1's purpose:**<br>- Store the canonical identity registry (ULID → public key)<br>- Provide the source of truth for identity verification<br>- Store verification tiers<br><br>**Why apps need L1:**<br>- To get the user's public key (can't verify signature without it)<br>- To check verification tier (trusted user or not)<br>- To ensure the identity is valid and not revoked<br><br>So the flow is:<br>1. User signs authorization request<br>2. App queries L1 to get user's public key<br>3. App verifies signature locally using that public key<br>4. App may also check verification tier from L1<br><br>**Revised Authorization:**<br><br>When a user opens an application, the app requests authorization. The user signs with their private key to connect. The app queries L1 to verify the signature and check the user's verification tier. Each app may have its own user system and require additional information.<br><br>Does this capture L1's role correctly? |\n| 03-13-2026, 11:53:55 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b540cebec6104c31941eb2923c7d\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Fri 2026-03-13 11:53 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: then what was option a? |\n| 03-13-2026, 11:54:16 | Assistant | [[reply_to_current]] You're right, I confused myself. Let me clarify:<br><br>**Option A: App verifies directly**<br>- App already has the public key (cached from previous L1 query)<br>- App verifies signature locally<br>- No L1 call needed for each authorization<br><br>**Option B: App calls L1 for each authorization**<br>- App sends signature to L1<br>- L1 verifies and returns result<br><br>The difference is **where verification happens**:<br>- Option A: App does it (using cached public key from L1)<br>- Option B: L1 does it (app delegates verification)<br><br>Both require L1 to get the public key initially. The question is: does the app verify signatures itself, or does it ask L1 to verify?<br><br>I think **Option A** is better — apps verify locally using the public key they got from L1. This is faster and more scalable.<br><br>But for the whitepaper, we don't need to specify implementation. We can just say:<br><br>**Authorization.**<br><br>When a user opens an application, the app requests authorization. The user signs with their private key to connect. The app verifies the signature through L1. Each app may have its own user system and require additional information.<br><br>\"Verifies through L1\" covers both options without getting into implementation details. Does this work? |\n| 03-13-2026, 12:01:16 | Assistant | Discussing whitepaper 5.3 Authorization section with Allan — clarifying L1's role in verification. |\n| 03-13-2026, 12:08:19 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b540c95c31ca4c45e30a831cfd09\",<br>  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",<br>  \"timestamp\": \"Fri 2026-03-13 12:08 GMT+8\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>Sender (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",<br>  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",<br>  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"<br>}<br>```<br>任亚伦: how can app know who the user's is? i think process is user send unique id and sign it, then app verify through l1? user never need send pubkey, just provide unique id. since it's multikey system. and l2 can't cache all l1 data. they check everytime arent they? this process need clarify |\n| 03-13-2026, 12:08:55 | Assistant | [[reply_to_current]] You're right, I need to think through this more carefully.<br><br>**The authorization flow:**<br><br>1. User opens app<br>2. User provides their unique ID (ULID) and signs something<br>3. App sends ULID + signature to L1<br>4. L1 looks up the public key for that ULID<br>5. L1 verifies the signature<br>6. L1 returns verification result to app<br><br>**Key points:**<br>- User only provides ULID (not public key)<br>- L1 stores ULID → public key mapping<br>- App doesn't cache all L1 data (too much)<br>- App queries L1 each time to verify<br><br>So the app doesn't verify locally — it asks L1 to verify. L1 is the source of truth.<br><br>**Revised Authorization:**<br><br>When a user opens an application, they provide their unique ID and sign the authorization request. The app sends the ID and signature to L1 for verification. L1 looks up the user's public key and verifies the signature. Once verified, the user is connected. Each app may have its own user system and require additional information.<br><br>Does this capture the flow correctly? |\n| 03-13-2026, 12:16:18 | Assistant | Discussing whitepaper 5.3 Authorization section with Allan — clarifying the verification flow through L1. |\n| 03-13-2026, 12:16:22 | User | Conversation info (untrusted metadata):<br>```json<br>{<br>  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b540cb79404a4c3b730e62a037a8\",<br>  