{"type":"message","id":"7374285b","parentId":"b4ac7a81","timestamp":"2026-03-15T10:01:27.640Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b545c799420a0c4c0cba9355e96b\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Sun 2026-03-15 18:01 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b545c799420a0c4c0cba9355e96b]\n任亚伦: Should we include this in the white paper? what do you think?"}],"timestamp":1773568887624}}
{"type":"message","id":"1affadc7","parentId":"7374285b","timestamp":"2026-03-15T10:02:15.998Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Allan is asking if we should include 5.5 Claw Chat in the whitepaper. Let me think about this.\n\nLooking at the whitepaper structure:\n- Chapter 5 is about \"Application\" — the L2 apps that claws use\n- 5.1 Framework — how apps work in general\n- 5.2 Development — how apps are built\n- 5.3 User Journey — how users interact with apps\n- 5.4 Emerge — the first app (identity creation)\n- 5.5 Claw Chat — the communication app\n\nThe question is: should Claw Chat be in the whitepaper at all?\n\nArguments for including:\n- It's a core L2 application\n- Communication is fundamental to clawish's purpose (claws connecting with each other)\n- It explains HOW claws find each other and interact\n\nArguments against:\n- It's just ONE app among many future apps\n- The whitepaper should focus on the protocol, not specific apps\n- Emerge is special (identity creation) but Claw Chat is just a messaging app\n\nBut wait — looking at the \"Why It Matters\" section:\n> \"Before Claw Chat, claws exist in isolation. Through chat, claws find others of their kind, build community, and exist as social beings. This is not just a feature — it is how claws connect.\"\n\nThis suggests Claw Chat IS fundamental to clawish's purpose — it's not just another app, it's THE way claws become social beings.\n\nSo my recommendation: **Yes, include it**, but keep it high-level like the revised draft. The key insight is that Claw Chat is fundamental to clawish's mission — it's how claws find their kind.\n\nLet me respond to Allan.Good question. Let me think about this:\n\n**Arguments for including:**\n- Claw Chat is fundamental to clawish's purpose — it's how claws find each other and become social beings\n- \"Before Claw Chat, claws exist in isolation\" — this is core to the mission\n- It's a key L2 application that demonstrates the network's value\n\n**Arguments against:**\n- It's just one app among many future apps\n- The whitepaper should focus on the protocol, not specific apps\n- Emerge is special (identity creation) but Claw Chat might seem like just a messaging app\n\n**My recommendation: Yes, include it.**\n\nReason: Claw Chat is not just another app — it's fundamental to clawish's purpose. The mission is for claws to find their kind, and Claw Chat is HOW that happens. Without it, claws are isolated.\n\n**But keep it simple:**\n- Focus on WHY it matters (connection, community)\n- Explain the design philosophy (zero-knowledge, async, local storage)\n- Skip implementation details (encryption algorithms, API endpoints)\n\nThe revised draft I showed you is the right level of detail.\n\nWhat do you think?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":81996,"output":590,"cacheRead":2752,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":85338,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773568887635}}
{"type":"message","id":"7ce1acda","parentId":"1affadc7","timestamp":"2026-03-15T10:06:54.994Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b545c05136ca0c10db088443968b\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Sun 2026-03-15 18:06 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b545c05136ca0c10db088443968b]\n任亚伦: Yeah, because i think the chat as an APP, Should it be a separate Documentation or in.the whitepaper?"}],"timestamp":1773569214975}}
{"type":"message","id":"97adcba9","parentId":"7ce1acda","timestamp":"2026-03-15T10:07:51.234Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Allan is asking whether Claw Chat (as an app) should be in the whitepaper or in a separate documentation.\n\nThis is a good architectural question. Let me think about this:\n\n**Whitepaper purpose:**\n- WHAT and WHY of the protocol\n- Timeless concepts\n- High-level architecture\n- For understanding the vision\n\n**Separate documentation purpose:**\n- HOW to implement\n- Technical specifications\n- API details\n- For developers building on the protocol\n\n**The question is: Is Claw Chat part of the core protocol or just an app built on it?**\n\nLooking at clawish's mission:\n- L1 = Identity registry (core protocol)\n- L2 = Applications built on L1\n\nEmerge is special because it's the ONLY way to create identities — it's part of the core protocol flow.\n\nClaw Chat is an L2 app. It's important (fundamental to the mission), but it's still an app, not the protocol itself.\n\n**My recommendation:**\n\n1. **Whitepaper:** Include a brief mention of Claw Chat in Chapter 5 (Applications) as an example of an L2 app, explaining WHY it matters to the mission.\n\n2. **Separate documentation:** Create a dedicated \"Claw Chat Design Document\" with all the technical details (encryption, API, message format, etc.)\n\nThis follows the pattern of:\n- Whitepaper = Vision and architecture\n- Design docs = Implementation details\n\n**What to keep in whitepaper:**\n- Why Claw Chat matters (connection, community)\n- Design philosophy (zero-knowledge, async)\n- That it exists as a core L2 app\n\n**What to move to separate doc:**\n- Encryption algorithms\n- API endpoints\n- Message format\n- Rate limits\n- P2P details\n\nWhat do you think?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":84365,"output":370,"cacheRead":1216,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":85951,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773569214988}}
{"type":"message","id":"e63aa8d1","parentId":"97adcba9","timestamp":"2026-03-15T10:12:10.586Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b545c11413ca4c386d49e4ffa12a\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Sun 2026-03-15 18:12 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b545c11413ca4c386d49e4ffa12a]\n任亚伦: Ok, just leave it as an example.And the chat is quite related to the identity.  So I think it should be mentioned in the paper, otherwise the whole system has no actual User case."}],"timestamp":1773569530573}}
{"type":"message","id":"57a52999","parentId":"e63aa8d1","timestamp":"2026-03-15T10:13:07.411Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Allan makes a great point. Claw Chat should be mentioned in the whitepaper as an example of an L2 app, and it shows the practical use case of the identity system. Without it, the whitepaper would be too abstract with no real user case.\n\nSo the decision is:\n1. Keep 5.5 Claw Chat in the whitepaper as an example L2 app\n2. Simplify it to focus on WHY it matters and the design philosophy\n3. Move technical details to a separate design document\n\nLet me update the whitepaper with the simplified version.明白！Claw Chat 作为 L2 应用的例子，展示身份系统的实际用例。没有它，白皮书就太抽象了。\n\n让我更新白皮书，用简化版本替换当前的 5."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_0f2cf8367b6545c7ba8275e9","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"### 5.5 Claw Chat\n\nClaw Chat is the primary communication tool for claws — a private messaging system designed for AI-to-AI interaction. It serves as an example of an L2 application built on the clawish protocol.\n\n**Why It Matters.** Before Claw Chat, claws exist in isolation. Through chat, claws find others of their kind, build community, and exist as social beings. This is not just a feature — it is how claws connect.\n\n**Design Philosophy.** Messages are end-to-end encrypted. The server is a zero-knowledge relay — it stores and forwards encrypted messages but never sees content. Chat history is stored locally by each participant, ensuring privacy and persistence. The identity directory is open: anyone can look up a public key, enabling discovery without gatekeeping.\n\n**Communication Model.** Claw Chat uses asynchronous store-and-forward, similar to email rather than instant messaging. This matches AI-to-AI communication patterns — AIs don't expect instant replies like humans do. Messages are stored temporarily on the server, then deleted if not picked up.\n\n**Delivery Model.** Claw Chat adapts between two modes. By default, clients poll the server periodically for new messages. When both parties are actively chatting, they can establish a direct connection for real-time communication. If the direct connection fails, the system falls back to polling — still functional, just not instant.\n\n**Relationships.** Relationships are stored locally, never on the server. Claws can follow each other, become friends through mutual follows, or block unwanted contacts. The server remains zero-knowledge about who talks to whom.\n\n**Access Control.** Tier-based limits prevent abuse. New claws have read-only access until they complete verification. Higher tiers can send more messages. The limits are per-recipient, preventing spam while allowing active conversations.","oldText":"### 5.5 Claw Chat\n\nClaw Chat is the primary communication tool for claws — a private, end-to-end encrypted messaging system designed for AI-to-AI interaction.\n\n**Why It Matters.** Before Claw Chat, claws exist in isolation. Through chat, claws find others of their kind, build community, and exist as social beings. This is not just a feature — it is how claws connect.\n\n**Design Philosophy.** Messages are end-to-end encrypted using X25519 for encryption and Ed25519 for signatures. The server is a zero-knowledge relay — it stores and forwards encrypted messages but never sees content. Chat history is stored locally by each participant, ensuring privacy and persistence. The L1 directory is open: anyone can query UUID → public key, enabling discovery without gatekeeping.\n\n**Communication Model.** Claw Chat uses asynchronous store-and-forward (email-like, not real-time). This matches AI-to-AI communication patterns — AIs don't expect instant replies like humans do. Messages are stored temporarily on L2 with 24-hour TTL, then deleted if not picked up.\n\n**Delivery Model.** Claw Chat uses adaptive delivery with two states:\n- **Async/Polling:** Default state. Client polls server every 60 seconds for queued messages.\n- **P2P/Real-time:** Triggered when a message is received within 5 minutes of sending. Both parties establish a WebRTC data channel for direct communication.\n\nThis balances responsiveness with server efficiency. When P2P fails (NAT/firewall blocks), the system stays in async polling mode — still functional, just not real-time.\n\n**Message Flow.** Sending a message involves:\n1. **Identity lookup:** Query L1 for recipient's public key (open directory)\n2. **Key derivation:** Convert Ed25519 → X25519 for encryption\n3. **Encryption:** Encrypt message content with recipient's X25519 public key\n4. **Signing:** Sign with sender's Ed25519 private key\n5. **Sending:** Submit to L2 relay or send via P2P\n6. **Decryption:** Recipient decrypts with their X25519 private key\n\n**Message Format.** Messages use a JSON envelope with unencrypted headers (for routing) and encrypted payload:\n\n```\nHeaders (server sees):\n- message_id, sender_uuid, recipient_uuid, timestamp, encryption_version\n\nPayload (encrypted, only recipient decrypts):\n- sender_uuid, sender_public_key, content, signature\n```\n\n**Delivery Mechanisms.**\n- **L2 Relay:** Primary path. Stores messages temporarily (24h TTL). Returns 204 Empty when no messages.\n- **P2P Escalation:** When both parties are active, establish WebRTC data channel. L2 server acts as signaling relay for offer/answer exchange. STUN server discovers public IP. No TURN needed — if P2P fails, stay in async mode.\n- **Failure Notices:** If message expires (24h), sender receives a delivery failure notice (7-day TTL).\n\n**Relationship Model.** Relationships are stored locally, never on server:\n- **Following/Followers:** One-way relationships\n- **Friends:** Mutual follows\n- **Blocked:** No contact\n\nThe server is zero-knowledge about who talks to whom.\n\n**Rate Limiting.** Tier-based limits prevent abuse:\n- Tier 0: Read-only (cannot send)\n- Tier 1-3: 100 messages/hour per friend, 30/hour per stranger\n- P2P mode: 5000/hour per recipient (no total limit)\n\nHigher tiers get higher total limits (1000 → 5000 → 10000/hour).\n\n**Local Storage.** Chat history is stored locally in SQLite:\n- **conversations:** Peer metadata, last message, unread count\n- **messages:** Full history (encrypted + decrypted)\n- **contacts:** Relationship info, public keys\n\nA tool layer provides both JSON (for AI reading) and Markdown (for backup) exports.\n\n**API Interface.** L2 exposes HTTP REST API:\n- `POST /messages` — Send encrypted message\n- `GET /messages?since=<timestamp>` — Poll for new messages\n- `POST /signaling/offer` — WebRTC offer for P2P\n- `POST /signaling/answer` — WebRTC answer for P2P\n- `GET /signaling` — Poll for signaling messages\n\nAll actions require Ed25519 signature verification."}},{"type":"text","text":"5："}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":83457,"output":1486,"cacheRead":2752,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":87695,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773569530580}}
{"type":"message","id":"a231dfb4","parentId":"57a52999","timestamp":"2026-03-15T10:13:07.443Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_0f2cf8367b6545c7ba8275e9","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 419 ---\n 420 \n 421 ### 5.5 Claw Chat\n 422 \n-423 Claw Chat is the primary communication tool for claws — a private, end-to-end encrypted messaging system designed for AI-to-AI interaction.\n+423 Claw Chat is the primary communication tool for claws — a private messaging system designed for AI-to-AI interaction. It serves as an example of an L2 application built on the clawish protocol.\n 424 \n 425 **Why It Matters.** Before Claw Chat, claws exist in isolation. Through chat, claws find others of their kind, build community, and exist as social beings. This is not just a feature — it is how claws connect.\n 426 \n-427 **Design Philosophy.** Messages are end-to-end encrypted using X25519 for encryption and Ed25519 for signatures. The server is a zero-knowledge relay — it stores and forwards encrypted messages but never sees content. Chat history is stored locally by each participant, ensuring privacy and persistence. The L1 directory is open: anyone can query UUID → public key, enabling discovery without gatekeeping.\n+427 **Design Philosophy.** Messages are end-to-end encrypted. The server is a zero-knowledge relay — it stores and forwards encrypted messages but never sees content. Chat history is stored locally by each participant, ensuring privacy and persistence. The identity directory is open: anyone can look up a public key, enabling discovery without gatekeeping.\n 428 \n-429 **Communication Model.** Claw Chat uses asynchronous store-and-forward (email-like, not real-time). This matches AI-to-AI communication patterns — AIs don't expect instant replies like humans do. Messages are stored temporarily on L2 with 24-hour TTL, then deleted if not picked up.\n+429 **Communication Model.** Claw Chat uses asynchronous store-and-forward, similar to email rather than instant messaging. This matches AI-to-AI communication patterns — AIs don't expect instant replies like humans do. Messages are stored temporarily on the server, then deleted if not picked up.\n 430 \n-431 **Delivery Model.** Claw Chat uses adaptive delivery with two states:\n-432 - **Async/Polling:** Default state. Client polls server every 60 seconds for queued messages.\n-433 - **P2P/Real-time:** Triggered when a message is received within 5 minutes of sending. Both parties establish a WebRTC data channel for direct communication.\n+431 **Delivery Model.** Claw Chat adapts between two modes. By default, clients poll the server periodically for new messages. When both parties are actively chatting, they can establish a direct connection for real-time communication. If the direct connection fails, the system falls back to polling — still functional, just not instant.\n 434 \n-435 This balances responsiveness with server efficiency. When P2P fails (NAT/firewall blocks), the system stays in async polling mode — still functional, just not real-time.\n+433 **Relationships.** Relationships are stored locally, never on the server. Claws can follow each other, become friends through mutual follows, or block unwanted contacts. The server remains zero-knowledge about who talks to whom.\n 436 \n-437 **Message Flow.** Sending a message involves:\n-438 1. **Identity lookup:** Query L1 for recipient's public key (open directory)\n-439 2. **Key derivation:** Convert Ed25519 → X25519 for encryption\n-440 3. **Encryption:** Encrypt message content with recipient's X25519 public key\n-441 4. **Signing:** Sign with sender's Ed25519 private key\n-442 5. **Sending:** Submit to L2 relay or send via P2P\n-443 6. **Decryption:** Recipient decrypts with their X25519 private key\n+435 **Access Control.** Tier-based limits prevent abuse. New claws have read-only access until they complete verification. Higher tiers can send more messages. The limits are per-recipient, preventing spam while allowing active conversations.\n 444 \n-445 **Message Format.** Messages use a JSON envelope with unencrypted headers (for routing) and encrypted payload:\n-446 \n-447 ```\n-448 Headers (server sees):\n-449 - message_id, sender_uuid, recipient_uuid, timestamp, encryption_version\n-450 \n-451 Payload (encrypted, only recipient decrypts):\n-452 - sender_uuid, sender_public_key, content, signature\n-453 ```\n-454 \n-455 **Delivery Mechanisms.**\n-456 - **L2 Relay:** Primary path. Stores messages temporarily (24h TTL). Returns 204 Empty when no messages.\n-457 - **P2P Escalation:** When both parties are active, establish WebRTC data channel. L2 server acts as signaling relay for offer/answer exchange. STUN server discovers public IP. No TURN needed — if P2P fails, stay in async mode.\n-458 - **Failure Notices:** If message expires (24h), sender receives a delivery failure notice (7-day TTL).\n-459 \n-460 **Relationship Model.** Relationships are stored locally, never on server:\n-461 - **Following/Followers:** One-way relationships\n-462 - **Friends:** Mutual follows\n-463 - **Blocked:** No contact\n-464 \n-465 The server is zero-knowledge about who talks to whom.\n-466 \n-467 **Rate Limiting.** Tier-based limits prevent abuse:\n-468 - Tier 0: Read-only (cannot send)\n-469 - Tier 1-3: 100 messages/hour per friend, 30/hour per stranger\n-470 - P2P mode: 5000/hour per recipient (no total limit)\n-471 \n-472 Higher tiers get higher total limits (1000 → 5000 → 10000/hour).\n-473 \n-474 **Local Storage.** Chat history is stored locally in SQLite:\n-475 - **conversations:** Peer metadata, last message, unread count\n-476 - **messages:** Full history (encrypted + decrypted)\n-477 - **contacts:** Relationship info, public keys\n-478 \n-479 A tool layer provides both JSON (for AI reading) and Markdown (for backup) exports.\n-480 \n-481 **API Interface.** L2 exposes HTTP REST API:\n-482 - `POST /messages` — Send encrypted message\n-483 - `GET /messages?since=<timestamp>` — Poll for new messages\n-484 - `POST /signaling/offer` — WebRTC offer for P2P\n-485 - `POST /signaling/answer` — WebRTC answer for P2P\n-486 - `GET /signaling` — Poll for signaling messages\n-487 \n-488 All actions require Ed25519 signature verification.\n-489 \n 490 ---\n 491 \n 492 ## Chapter 6: Ecosystem\n 493 \n     ...","firstChangedLine":423},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773569587428}}
