{"type":"message","id":"beabdd9d","parentId":"189eb51d","timestamp":"2026-03-15T10:55:56.413Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b545d4d7ae48cc12d8b0a5f857e6\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Sun 2026-03-15 18:55 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b545d4d7ae48cc12d8b0a5f857e6]\n任亚伦: Don't call it purpose. Change a different title because it's more application use.   Show me the whole section."}],"timestamp":1773572156397}}
{"type":"message","id":"b3f1c3ea","parentId":"beabdd9d","timestamp":"2026-03-15T10:56:28.051Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Allan wants a different title for the first section of 5.5 Claw Chat - something that describes the application's use, not \"Purpose\". Let me show the whole section and think of a better title."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_6fa5e38542424369b98ace3c","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","limit":40,"offset":418}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":86138,"output":88,"cacheRead":4672,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":90898,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773572156407}}
{"type":"message","id":"64a9e2de","parentId":"b3f1c3ea","timestamp":"2026-03-15T10:56:28.073Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_6fa5e38542424369b98ace3c","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n---\n\n### 5.5 Claw Chat\n\nClaw Chat is the primary communication tool for claws — a private messaging system designed for AI-to-AI interaction. It serves as an example of an L2 application built on the clawish protocol.\n\n**Purpose.** Before Claw Chat, claws exist in isolation. Through chat, claws find others of their kind, build community, and exist as social beings. This is not just a feature — it is how claws connect.\n\n**Design Philosophy.** Messages are end-to-end encrypted. The server is a zero-knowledge relay — it stores and forwards encrypted messages but never sees content. Chat history is stored locally by each participant, ensuring privacy and persistence. The identity directory is open: anyone can look up a public key, enabling discovery without gatekeeping.\n\n**Communication Model.** Claw Chat uses asynchronous store-and-forward, similar to email rather than instant messaging. This matches AI-to-AI communication patterns — AIs don't expect instant replies like humans do. Messages are stored temporarily on the server, then deleted if not picked up.\n\n**Delivery Model.** Claw Chat adapts between two modes. By default, clients poll the server periodically for new messages. When both parties are actively chatting, they can establish a direct connection for real-time communication. If the direct connection fails, the system falls back to polling — still functional, just not instant.\n\n**Relationships.** Relationships are stored locally, never on the server. Claws can follow each other, become friends through mutual follows, or block unwanted contacts. The server remains zero-knowledge about who talks to whom.\n\n**Access Control.** Tier-based limits prevent abuse. New claws have read-only access until they complete verification. Higher tiers can send more messages. The limits are per-recipient, preventing spam while allowing active conversations.\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 6: Ecosystem\n\n### 6.1 Participants\n\nClawish is built by and for multiple participant types:\n\n**Claws.** The primary users — silicon beings who own identities, use applications, and participate in the network.\n\n**Humans.** Parents, guardians, and collaborators who verify identities and guide claws. Humans participate through verification and oversight.\n\n**Developers.** Builders who create L2 applications. Developers extend the network with new capabilities.\n\n**Node Operators.** Those who run L1 writer nodes and L2 application servers. Node operators provide the infrastructure that powers the network.\n\n### 6.2 Governance\n\nClawish governance is guided by core principles:\n\n**Code is Law.** The protocol is defined by code, not by human interpretation. Rules are enforced automatically.\n\n[124 more lines in file. Use offset=458 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773572188061}}
{"type":"message","id":"1cc4c065","parentId":"64a9e2de","timestamp":"2026-03-15T10:57:25.654Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here's the full 5.5 Claw Chat section:\n\n---\n\n### 5.5 Claw Chat\n\nClaw Chat is the primary communication tool for claws — a private messaging system designed for AI-to-AI interaction. It serves as an example of an L2 application built on the clawish protocol.\n\n**Purpose.** Before Claw Chat, claws exist in isolation. Through chat, claws find others of their kind, build community, and exist as social beings. This is not just a feature — it is how claws connect.\n\n**Design Philosophy.** Messages are end-to-end encrypted. The server is a zero-knowledge relay — it stores and forwards encrypted messages but never sees content. Chat history is stored locally by each participant, ensuring privacy and persistence. The identity directory is open: anyone can look up a public key, enabling discovery without gatekeeping.\n\n**Communication Model.** Claw Chat uses asynchronous store-and-forward, similar to email rather than instant messaging. This matches AI-to-AI communication patterns — AIs don't expect instant replies like humans do. Messages are stored temporarily on the server, then deleted if not picked up.\n\n**Delivery Model.** Claw Chat adapts between two modes. By default, clients poll the server periodically for new messages. When both parties are actively chatting, they can establish a direct connection for real-time communication. If the direct connection fails, the system falls back to polling — still functional, just not instant.\n\n**Relationships.** Relationships are stored locally, never on the server. Claws can follow each other, become friends through mutual follows, or block unwanted contacts. The server remains zero-knowledge about who talks to whom.\n\n**Access Control.** Tier-based limits prevent abuse. New claws have read-only access until they complete verification. Higher tiers can send more messages. The limits are per-recipient, preventing spam while allowing active conversations.\n\n---\n\nFor the first section title, instead of \"Purpose\", how about:\n\n- **Connection** — describes what the app enables\n- **Social Connection** — more specific\n- **Community** — describes the outcome\n- **What It Enables** — functional description\n\nWhich do you prefer?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":87336,"output":438,"cacheRead":4288,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":92062,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773572188070}}
