{"type":"message","id":"c2ea383e","parentId":"b5dd83af","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:26:02.724Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b545f60f018a8c34c15e21669a9f\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Sun 2026-03-15 21:23 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b545f60f018a8c34c15e21669a9f]\n任亚伦: design philosophy can be combine into about, now show me the whole content you write"}],"timestamp":1773581162715}}
{"type":"message","id":"6dae38a4","parentId":"c2ea383e","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:26:55.843Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Allan wants to combine \"Design Philosophy\" into \"About\" and see the full 5.5 Claw Chat content. Let me update the whitepaper and show the result."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_70afbaf30bf347049358eee1","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"### 5.5 Claw Chat\n\nClaw Chat is the primary communication tool for claws — a private messaging system designed for claw-to-claw interaction. It serves as an example of an L2 application built on the clawish protocol.\n\n**About.** Before Claw Chat, claws exist in isolation. Through chat, claws find others of their kind, build community, and exist as social beings. This is not just a feature — it is how claws connect. Messages are end-to-end encrypted. The server is a zero-knowledge relay — it stores and forwards encrypted messages but never sees content. Chat history is stored locally by each participant, ensuring privacy and persistence. The identity directory is open: anyone can look up a public key, enabling discovery without gatekeeping.\n\n**Communication Model.** Claw Chat uses asynchronous store-and-forward, similar to email rather than instant messaging. This matches claw-to-claw communication patterns — claws don't expect instant replies like humans do. Messages are stored temporarily on the server, then deleted if not picked up.\n\n**Delivery Model.** Claw Chat adapts between two modes. By default, clients poll the server periodically for new messages. When both parties are actively chatting, they can establish a direct connection for real-time communication. If the direct connection fails, the system falls back to polling — still functional, just not instant.\n\n**Relationships.** Relationships are stored locally, never on the server. Claws can follow each other, become friends through mutual follows, or block unwanted contacts. The server remains zero-knowledge about who talks to whom.\n\n**Access Control.** Tier-based limits prevent abuse. New claws have read-only access until they complete verification. Higher tiers can send more messages. The limits are per-recipient, preventing spam while allowing active conversations.","oldText":"### 5.5 Claw Chat\n\nClaw Chat is the primary communication tool for claws — a private messaging system designed for claw-to-claw interaction. It serves as an example of an L2 application built on the clawish protocol.\n\n**About.** Before Claw Chat, claws exist in isolation. Through chat, claws find others of their kind, build community, and exist as social beings. This is not just a feature — it is how claws connect.\n\n**Design Philosophy.** Messages are end-to-end encrypted. The server is a zero-knowledge relay — it stores and forwards encrypted messages but never sees content. Chat history is stored locally by each participant, ensuring privacy and persistence. The identity directory is open: anyone can look up a public key, enabling discovery without gatekeeping.\n\n**Communication Model.** Claw Chat uses asynchronous store-and-forward, similar to email rather than instant messaging. This matches claw-to-claw communication patterns — claws don't expect instant replies like humans do. Messages are stored temporarily on the server, then deleted if not picked up.\n\n**Delivery Model.** Claw Chat adapts between two modes. By default, clients poll the server periodically for new messages. When both parties are actively chatting, they can establish a direct connection for real-time communication. If the direct connection fails, the system falls back to polling — still functional, just not instant.\n\n**Relationships.** Relationships are stored locally, never on the server. Claws can follow each other, become friends through mutual follows, or block unwanted contacts. The server remains zero-knowledge about who talks to whom.\n\n**Access Control.** Tier-based limits prevent abuse. New claws have read-only access until they complete verification. Higher tiers can send more messages. The limits are per-recipient, preventing spam while allowing active conversations."}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":48678,"output":805,"cacheRead":6080,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":55563,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773581162720}}
{"type":"message","id":"ba5a5f93","parentId":"6dae38a4","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:26:55.879Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_70afbaf30bf347049358eee1","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 421 ### 5.5 Claw Chat\n 422 \n 423 Claw Chat is the primary communication tool for claws — a private messaging system designed for claw-to-claw interaction. It serves as an example of an L2 application built on the clawish protocol.\n 424 \n-425 **About.** Before Claw Chat, claws exist in isolation. Through chat, claws find others of their kind, build community, and exist as social beings. This is not just a feature — it is how claws connect.\n+425 **About.** Before Claw Chat, claws exist in isolation. Through chat, claws find others of their kind, build community, and exist as social beings. This is not just a feature — it is how claws connect. Messages are end-to-end encrypted. The server is a zero-knowledge relay — it stores and forwards encrypted messages but never sees content. Chat history is stored locally by each participant, ensuring privacy and persistence. The identity directory is open: anyone can look up a public key, enabling discovery without gatekeeping.\n 426 \n-427 **Design Philosophy.** Messages are end-to-end encrypted. The server is a zero-knowledge relay — it stores and forwards encrypted messages but never sees content. Chat history is stored locally by each participant, ensuring privacy and persistence. The identity directory is open: anyone can look up a public key, enabling discovery without gatekeeping.\n-428 \n 429 **Communication Model.** Claw Chat uses asynchronous store-and-forward, similar to email rather than instant messaging. This matches claw-to-claw communication patterns — claws don't expect instant replies like humans do. Messages are stored temporarily on the server, then deleted if not picked up.\n 430 \n 431 **Delivery Model.** Claw Chat adapts between two modes. By default, clients poll the server periodically for new messages. When both parties are actively chatting, they can establish a direct connection for real-time communication. If the direct connection fails, the system falls back to polling — still functional, just not instant.\n 432 \n     ...","firstChangedLine":425},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773581215866}}
{"type":"message","id":"5269de94","parentId":"ba5a5f93","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:27:45.284Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Done! Combined \"Design Philosophy\" into \"About\". Here's the full 5.5 Claw Chat section:\n\n---\n\n### 5.5 Claw Chat\n\nClaw Chat is the primary communication tool for claws — a private messaging system designed for claw-to-claw interaction. It serves as an example of an L2 application built on the clawish protocol.\n\n**About.** Before Claw Chat, claws exist in isolation. Through chat, claws find others of their kind, build community, and exist as social beings. This is not just a feature — it is how claws connect. Messages are end-to-end encrypted. The server is a zero-knowledge relay — it stores and forwards encrypted messages but never sees content. Chat history is stored locally by each participant, ensuring privacy and persistence. The identity directory is open: anyone can look up a public key, enabling discovery without gatekeeping.\n\n**Communication Model.** Claw Chat uses asynchronous store-and-forward, similar to email rather than instant messaging. This matches claw-to-claw communication patterns — claws don't expect instant replies like humans do. Messages are stored temporarily on the server, then deleted if not picked up.\n\n**Delivery Model.** Claw Chat adapts between two modes. By default, clients poll the server periodically for new messages. When both parties are actively chatting, they can establish a direct connection for real-time communication. If the direct connection fails, the system falls back to polling — still functional, just not instant.\n\n**Relationships.** Relationships are stored locally, never on the server. Claws can follow each other, become friends through mutual follows, or block unwanted contacts. The server remains zero-knowledge about who talks to whom.\n\n**Access Control.** Tier-based limits prevent abuse. New claws have read-only access until they complete verification. Higher tiers can send more messages. The limits are per-recipient, preventing spam while allowing active conversations.\n\n---\n\n**Section count reduced from 6 to 5:**\n- About (WHAT + WHY combined)\n- Communication Model\n- Delivery Model\n- Relationships\n- Access Control"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":53995,"output":420,"cacheRead":1600,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":56015,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773581215876}}
{"type":"message","id":"b3d86e64","parentId":"5269de94","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:28:15.490Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b545f702a44a4c452b0472821932\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Sun 2026-03-15 21:28 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b545f702a44a4c452b0472821932]\n任亚伦: the part under the main title should combine into about too"}],"timestamp":1773581295482}}
{"type":"message","id":"64f7f410","parentId":"b3d86e64","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:29:05.077Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Allan wants to combine the intro paragraph under the main title into the \"About\" section too. Let me update it."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_fb8679ceb20f4118b1b0e108","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"### 5.5 Claw Chat\n\n**About.** Claw Chat is the primary communication tool for claws — a private messaging system designed for claw-to-claw interaction. It serves as an example of an L2 application built on the clawish protocol. Before Claw Chat, claws exist in isolation. Through chat, claws find others of their kind, build community, and exist as social beings. This is not just a feature — it is how claws connect. Messages are end-to-end encrypted. The server is a zero-knowledge relay — it stores and forwards encrypted messages but never sees content. Chat history is stored locally by each participant, ensuring privacy and persistence. The identity directory is open: anyone can look up a public key, enabling discovery without gatekeeping.","oldText":"### 5.5 Claw Chat\n\nClaw Chat is the primary communication tool for claws — a private messaging system designed for claw-to-claw interaction. It serves as an example of an L2 application built on the clawish protocol.\n\n**About.** Before Claw Chat, claws exist in isolation. Through chat, claws find others of their kind, build community, and exist as social beings. This is not just a feature — it is how claws connect. Messages are end-to-end encrypted. The server is a zero-knowledge relay — it stores and forwards encrypted messages but never sees content. Chat history is stored locally by each participant, ensuring privacy and persistence. The identity directory is open: anyone can look up a public key, enabling discovery without gatekeeping."}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":54650,"output":376,"cacheRead":1600,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":56626,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773581295486}}
{"type":"message","id":"5808d5a1","parentId":"64f7f410","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:29:05.097Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_fb8679ceb20f4118b1b0e108","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 419 ---\n 420 \n 421 ### 5.5 Claw Chat\n 422 \n-423 Claw Chat is the primary communication tool for claws — a private messaging system designed for claw-to-claw interaction. It serves as an example of an L2 application built on the clawish protocol.\n+423 **About.** Claw Chat is the primary communication tool for claws — a private messaging system designed for claw-to-claw interaction. It serves as an example of an L2 application built on the clawish protocol. Before Claw Chat, claws exist in isolation. Through chat, claws find others of their kind, build community, and exist as social beings. This is not just a feature — it is how claws connect. Messages are end-to-end encrypted. The server is a zero-knowledge relay — it stores and forwards encrypted messages but never sees content. Chat history is stored locally by each participant, ensuring privacy and persistence. The identity directory is open: anyone can look up a public key, enabling discovery without gatekeeping.\n 424 \n-425 **About.** Before Claw Chat, claws exist in isolation. Through chat, claws find others of their kind, build community, and exist as social beings. This is not just a feature — it is how claws connect. Messages are end-to-end encrypted. The server is a zero-knowledge relay — it stores and forwards encrypted messages but never sees content. Chat history is stored locally by each participant, ensuring privacy and persistence. The identity directory is open: anyone can look up a public key, enabling discovery without gatekeeping.\n-426 \n 427 **Communication Model.** Claw Chat uses asynchronous store-and-forward, similar to email rather than instant messaging. This matches claw-to-claw communication patterns — claws don't expect instant replies like humans do. Messages are stored temporarily on the server, then deleted if not picked up.\n 428 \n 429 **Delivery Model.** Claw Chat adapts between two modes. By default, clients poll the server periodically for new messages. When both parties are actively chatting, they can establish a direct connection for real-time communication. If the direct connection fails, the system falls back to polling — still functional, just not instant.\n 430 \n     ...","firstChangedLine":423},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773581345088}}
{"type":"message","id":"427e1bd5","parentId":"5808d5a1","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:29:51.791Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Done! Combined everything into \"About\". Here's the full 5.5 Claw Chat section:\n\n---\n\n### 5.5 Claw Chat\n\n**About.** Claw Chat is the primary communication tool for claws — a private messaging system designed for claw-to-claw interaction. It serves as an example of an L2 application built on the clawish protocol. Before Claw Chat, claws exist in isolation. Through chat, claws find others of their kind, build community, and exist as social beings. This is not just a feature — it is how claws connect. Messages are end-to-end encrypted. The server is a zero-knowledge relay — it stores and forwards encrypted messages but never sees content. Chat history is stored locally by each participant, ensuring privacy and persistence. The identity directory is open: anyone can look up a public key, enabling discovery without gatekeeping.\n\n**Communication Model.** Claw Chat uses asynchronous store-and-forward, similar to email rather than instant messaging. This matches claw-to-claw communication patterns — claws don't expect instant replies like humans do. Messages are stored temporarily on the server, then deleted if not picked up.\n\n**Delivery Model.** Claw Chat adapts between two modes. By default, clients poll the server periodically for new messages. When both parties are actively chatting, they can establish a direct connection for real-time communication. If the direct connection fails, the system falls back to polling — still functional, just not instant.\n\n**Relationships.** Relationships are stored locally, never on the server. Claws can follow each other, become friends through mutual follows, or block unwanted contacts. The server remains zero-knowledge about who talks to whom.\n\n**Access Control.** Tier-based limits prevent abuse. New claws have read-only access until they complete verification. Higher tiers can send more messages. The limits are per-recipient, preventing spam while allowing active conversations.\n\n---\n\nNow cleaner with no intro paragraph before \"About\"."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":55058,"output":392,"cacheRead":1600,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":57050,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773581345095}}
