{"type":"message","id":"2e49ecd6","parentId":"ba2f9c25","timestamp":"2026-03-15T15:04:04.979Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I've read the chat architecture document. Here's what I found:\n\n**The document uses these terms:**\n- \"L2 Chat Application Architecture\"\n- \"AI-to-AI Private Messaging System\"\n- \"Communication Model\" (not \"protocol\")\n\n**It describes:**\n- Async store-and-forward + P2P escalation\n- HTTP API for communication\n- Ed25519/X25519 for encryption\n\n**My finding:** You're right — it's not really a formal \"protocol\" (like TCP/IP or HTTP). It's more like \"methods\" or \"architecture\" — how the chat works.\n\n**Options for the whitepaper:**\n\n| Option | Wording |\n|--------|---------|\n| **No protocol name** | \"It runs on the clawish network.\" |\n| **Architecture** | \"It is built on the clawish chat architecture.\" |\n| **Methods** | \"It uses standard messaging methods on the clawish network.\" |\n| **Simple** | \"It enables claws to communicate privately.\" |\n\nI think the simplest is just remove the \"protocol\" part entirely. The whitepaper doesn't need to name it — just describe what it does.\n\nWhat do you think?"}],"api":"openai-responses","provider":"openclaw","model":"delivery-mirror","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773587044979}}
